03680nam a22006255i 9780292756045DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211979txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927560457 a10.7560/7242732doi  a(DE-B1597)587794  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1219.3.R38 7aREL0720002bisacsh04a299.71 aBrundage, Burr Cartwright, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Fifth Sun :bAztec Gods, Aztec World /cBurr Cartwright Brundage. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1979  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. The World, the Heavens, and Time -- t2. Creation and the Role of Paradise -- t3. The Quality of the Numinous -- t4. Tezcatlipoca -- t5. Quetzalcoatl -- t6. The Making of Huitzilopochtli -- t7. The Goddesses -- t8. Man -- t9. The Nuclear Cult: War, Sacrifice, and Cannibalism -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe ancient Aztecs dwelt at the center of a dazzling and complex cosmos. From this position they were acutely receptive to the demands of their gods. The Fifth Sun represents a dramatic overview of the Aztec conception of the universe and the gods who populated it—Quetzalcoatl, the Plumed Serpent; Tezcatlipoca, the Smoking Mirror; and Huitzilopochtli, the Southern Hummingbird. Burr Cartwright Brundage explores the myths behind these and others in the Aztec pantheon in a way that illuminates both the human and the divine in Aztec life. The cult of human sacrifice is a pervasive theme in this study. It is a concept that permeated Aztec mythology and was the central preoccupation of the aggressive Aztec state. Another particularly interesting belief explored here is the “mask pool,” whereby gods could exchange regalia and, thus, identities. This vivid and eminently readable study also covers the use of hallucinogens; cannibalism; the calendars of ancient Mexico; tlachtli, the life-and-death ball game; the flower wars; divine transfiguration; and the evolution of the war god of the Mexica. A splendid introduction to Aztec religion, The Fifth Sun also contains insights for specialists in ethnohistory, mythology, and religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAztecsxReligion. 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Roy E.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72427340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292756045423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292756045/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK